  <Placemark>
    <name>Christ Lutheran Church</name>
    <description><![CDATA[Noack community<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 6730 FM 112, Taylor<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> In the mid-1880s, Lutheran families living at the Wendish settlement, Hochkirk, met in homes for church services. Local Pastor Gotthilf Birkmann began to officiate these meetings. Peter Zieschang, founder of Hochkirk, donated three acres of land for the site of a church. In 1891, at the cost of $200, the community dedicated a newly built church. In 1902, Hochkirk was renamed Noack, after postmaster John Ernest Noack. A parochial school was established at the church that taught separate German and English classes. Church services were in German until 1922, when English was gradually introduced. By the mid-1940s, all services were held in English. The present church building was completed in 1916 and is still in use. (2016)]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.385148,30.560636,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>[PENDING] Citizens Memorial Cemetery</name>
    <description><![CDATA[<b>⚠ PENDING — marker may not yet be installed at this location.</b><br/><br/>CR 265, S side between Wolf Ranch Pkwy. and Wolf Lakes Dr. Marker pending. Map dot approximate.<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> CR 265, Georgetown]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.696965,30.634336,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>David Hutcheson McFadin</name>
    <description><![CDATA[McFadin Cemetery (a.k.a. Comanche Peak Cemetery), off Comanche Bluff Road, off FM 1331<br/><br/><b>Address:</b> 401-805 Comanche Bluff, Circleville<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Served in the Texas War for Independence. Soldier at San Jacinto. Erected by the State of Texas 1962]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.417547,30.644101,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
  <Placemark>
    <name>Dog Run Log Cabin</name>
    <description><![CDATA[<b>Address:</b> 675 CR 202 East, Liberty Hill<br/><br/><b>Marker Text:</b> Built 1851 by Wm. Williams, settler from Arkansas. Owned 1901-1956 by family of A. Buck, also from Arkansas. Wood -- cypress, oak, cedar -- and stone were cut by hand; logs are joined by wooden pegs. Solidly built rooms are separated by a "dog run." Recorded Texas Historic Landmark - 1968]]></description>
    <Point><coordinates>-97.907076,30.731888,0</coordinates></Point>
  </Placemark>
